questions.question:
Consider the code fragment written in C below:

void f(int n) {
  if (n <= 1) {
    printf("%d", n);
  } else {
    f(n/2);
    printf("%d", n%2);
  }
}

What does f(173) print?

A. 01101101
B. 10110101
C. 10110101
D. 10101101

Consider the code fragment written in C below:

void f(int n) {
  if (n <= 1) {
    printf("%d", n);
  } else {
    f(n/2);
    printf("%d", n%2);
  }
}

Which of the following implementations will produce the same output for f(173) as the above code?

P1:
void f1(int n) {
  if (n > 1) f1(n/2);
  printf("%d", n%2);
}

P2:
void f2(int n) {
  int mask = 1;
  while (mask <= n) mask = mask * 2;
  mask = mask / 2;
  while (mask >= 1) {
    printf("%d", (n & mask) ? 1 : 0);
    mask = mask / 2;
  }
}

A. Both P1 and P2
B. P2 only
C. P1 only
D. Neither P1 nor P2
